        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 51-year-old man from the Czech Republic who comes in because of persistent muscle pain [SNOMED:M79.1]. He describes the discomfort as a diffuse aching in his muscles that has been troubling him enough to limit his normal daily activities [SNOMED:M79.1]. He looks tired but not acutely ill, walks into the clinic independently, and is able to hold a full conversation. He works a regular job and tries to stay active on weekends with light home projects and short walks, but lately he has been avoiding heavier activity because the muscle pain flares with exertion [SNOMED:M79.1].\n\nAt home, {patientName} lives with his family and keeps a fairly structured routine. He enjoys practical hobbies such as gardening and do-it-yourself repairs, and he usually prefers to manage minor health problems conservatively before seeking care. Over the past several days, however, the muscle pain has become noticeable enough that his spouse encouraged him to get evaluated [SNOMED:M79.1]. He denies dramatic focal injury and instead describes a bothersome generalized soreness centered in the muscles [SNOMED:M79.1].\n\nIn the exam room, {patientName} appears mildly uncomfortable when changing position on the chair because of the aching sensation in his muscles [SNOMED:M79.1]. He is worried that the pain may represent something more serious, especially because it has not resolved with rest alone. Despite the discomfort, he remains attentive, cooperative, and motivated to understand the cause and get symptom relief."
          }
        ]
      }
